<h1>Division of Psychology</h1>
<p>What is Psychology?  The study of psychology is concerned with people's motivation, behaviour and thought processes to determine how and why they act in a particular way. If you are interested in people, what they do and why they do it, psychology is for you. Psychologists want to understand and explain human experience such as emotions, memory, thoughts, dreams and criminality. When you study psychology at Abertay you will be introduced to the questions that intrigue psychologists and to the methods they use to find answers to those questions.</p>
<h3>Courses</h3>
<a href="../../Courses/CDetails.cfm?RID=4&CID=170" tabindex="10" title="BSc (Hons) Behavioural Science">BSc (Hons) Behavioural Science</a>
<p>Behavioural scientists are interested in all aspects of our lives and behaviour. They ask questions about how people behave and about the society they live in. They want to understand the effects our culture has on us and the effects we have on our culture and they try to find answers to the practical every-day problems we all encounter.</p>
<p>In our Behavioural Science course you will learn about how people think, act and interact in society. You will learn scientific methods of investigating behaviour and how to analyse and interpret it. In the first two years, you will study the foundations of psychology and sociology, as well as relevant aspects of IT and research methods. In third and fourth year, you will be able to study sociology topics such as health sociology, crime and deviance, social movements, gender studies and sociologies of Scotland, as well as psychology topics such as health psychology, sport psychology, language development, abnormal psychology, and clinical psychology. On completion of this course, you will possess a sound understanding of research methods, and will be able to draw upon a wide range of knowledge to apply to practical, every day problems.</p>
<p>Please note that at the end of year two, if you decide you would like to specialise in sociology or in psychology you may do so and will go on to graduate with BSc Sociology or BSc Psychology.</p>
 
<a href="../../Courses/CDetails.cfm?RID=4&CID=206" tabindex="11" title="BSc (Hons) Forensic Psychobiology">BSc (Hons) Forensic Psychobiology</a>
<p>This, very popular, BPS accredited course is a unique course that investigates criminal behaviour from a psychological perspective, along with the study of relevant life sciences. You will study criminality, personality, deviant behaviour and mental health issues to find out why people offend. You will also learn about Human physiology, forensic biology and chemistry to help you understand more about why crimes are committed. During the first two years, you will study the basic foundations in both subject areas and then you will have the opportunity to study more topics that have a specifically forensic focus. As in the BSc Psychology programme, you will receive training in research methods throughout the programme.</p>

<a href="../../Courses/CDetails.cfm?RID=4&CID=236" tabindex="12" title="BSc (Hons) Psychology">BSc (Hons) Psychology</a> 
<p>This BPS accredited programme aims to provide you with the foundations of the behavioural sciences. In the first two years, you will study psychology and sociology, as well as relevant aspects of IT and research methods. At the end of the second year, you will be ready to specialise in psychology alone. You will then be able to study a wide selection of topics over the next two years such as health psychology, sport psychology, language development, abnormal psychology, clinical psychology and others. When you have completed this course, you will possess a sound understanding of research methods, and will be able to draw upon a wide range of knowledge to apply to practical, every day problems. </p>
<p> <a href="../../Courses/CDetails.cfm?RID=4&amp;CID=239">BSc (Hons) Sociology<br />
</a>Sociology is the study of how people think, act and organise themselves. In this degree you will consider issues related to social democracy and discuss the development of sociological thought and the formation of industrial society. By the end of your degree you will have gained an appreciation of both classical and contemporary sociological theories. You will have developed your critical reasoning skills and be able to collect and manipulate both quantitative and qualitative data. </p>
<p>BSc (Hons) Sociology provides you with the opportunity to explore key sociological issues and debates including those on the changing nature of modern society, the media, identity and nationhood, and the regulation of gender, sexuality and the body. This degree will also enable you to engage with contemporary social and cultural theory which is essential for making sense of the modern world.</p>
<p>BSc (Hons) Sociology shares a common first two years with the Behavioural Science programme specialising in Sociology in the third and fourth years. In the first two years you will concentrate on foundation modules in Sociology and Psychology, together with modules in research methods, information technology and study skills.</p>
